My Review: This books defines various emotionally immature behavior and how it stems from parents. Difficultly to reflect and be in touch with your deepest selves, avoidance, internalizing/externalizing, over-intellectualization could be some coping traits. This book helps identifies such behavior in yourself and those around you and how it affects finding future partners. This book also describes traits of emotionally mature citing notable papers in psychology. Overall a good read!

Title: How to Be an Adult in Relationships: The Five Keys to Mindful Loving
Author: David Richo
My Review:
3.5 stars. Interesting book. I usually avoid reading books on this topic, so it was an interesting read. Author is a psychotherapist who jots down his experience and recommendations post observing many cases. I did not agree with author fully and I do not have enough data points to judge the validity of his methods. However, this book does a great job providing an overview of relationship, subconscious needs, typical fallacies, etc. Definitely wished having read this earlier.

I liked Ch 3 which provides a general overview; read it with a grain of salt. Read this chapter if short on time.

Title: Cosmos
Author: Carl Sagan
My Review: Absolutely amazing book and TV series and a great introduction to astronomy. Carl Sagan weaves a beautiful story of cosmos with stories of Ancient Greece, evolution of physics and scientific method, myths of Mars, etc. It is easy to understand why the series gained immense popularity and able to spark an enthusiasm for astronomy. Highly recommended!

Title: Poor Charlie's Almanack: The Wit and Wisdom of Charles T. Munger
Author: Charles T. Munger
My Review:
Charlie Munger seems a broad thinker and interested in reading various topics. He seems to draw inspiration from multiple disciplines like card games, psychology, history, sciences, etc. One of my main takeaways from this book has been being multi-disciplinary, and building a latticework of mental models and hang your experience in there.

Some important points listed here: https://fs.blog/munger-worldly-wisdom/

———————

Currently at 1/3rd progress, thought to review the good parts lest I forget.

The first two chapters (not written by Charlie Munger) is a compilation of opinion of Charlier Munger from his friends and associates. It feels very vacuous and a poor attempt to compile a biography. Third Chapter is again bits and pieces of information by Charlie.

Fourth Chapter is a compilation of his independent speeches and writing which has great nuggets of information! There are some generic advice splattered with good-to-great ones. Few things I liked:

1. Harvard commencement speech: Munger describes what should one do to be completely miserable in life. (Chemicals/drugs, envy, resentment, being unrealiable, learn everything you possibly can from your own personal experiences, minimizing objectivity, etc). I liked the negative approach of this delivery, since it creates a greater impression than a positive approach. Perhaps I will use this approach once.

https://jamesclear.com/great-speeches/how-to-guarantee-a-life-of-misery-by-charlie-munger

2. Emphasis on mental models and understanding limitation of our cognitive apparatus
https://fs.blog/great-talks/psychology-human-misjudgment/

3. Emphasis on scientific method: One specific line which captured my attention:
"Most people early achieve and later intensify a tendency to process new and discomforting information so that any original conclusion remains intact."
He seems a fan of Darwin who "gave priority attention to evidence tending to disconfirm whatever cherished and hard-won theory he already had".

4. Great emphasis on understanding human psychology

5. Advantages of micro-specialization,
facets of microeconomics
... and more.

Really enjoying the fourth chapter. If you have read similar books before there might not be a lot of new content; Though it seems a fun and easy read, a lot of overlap with generally sound advice and gives an insight into typical areas of focus for an investment professional.

Title: The Pragmatic Programmer: From Journeyman to Master
Author: Andy Hunt
My Review:
This is one of my favorite meta-technical books that I read early in my career and has helped me immensely. I will go as far as to say, If you need to read one technical book in your career, this should be it.

The book presents broad frameworks on approaching your software career and building good software. There are some fun anecdotal stories “Stone Soup and Boiled Frogs”, top highlights of the chapter marked as Tips to help remember the content, how to deal with software entropy i.e. code rot, building situational awareness, etc. Re-reading the book now (after 10 years in the software industry, working with multiple languages, frameworks, and industries), I’ve come to appreciate the timelessness of its concepts.

Title: Exhalation
Author: Ted Chiang
My Review:
Fascinating stories on time travel, AI, language, often reminding you of Black mirror. My personal favourite stories were The Lifecycle of Software Objects since it directly relates to my field of work.
Second fav was The Merchant and the Alchemist’s gate exploring various human emotions (success, remorse, greed, ..) in an immutable time travel setting (past and future is fixed). Special points for finer details on Arabian/Egyptian backdrop which immediately transports you to a far away land and time period.
